What you can then do is import whatever data structures you decide you need from your standard library, and implement them. In your case, the solution is not so simple because you'll have to build up your custom data structure from raw data. Fortunately, even that task doesn't have to be too daunting. After all, you're allowed to write more code than your problem requires, so in effect, you're allowed about one page of code for every question to do whatever you want! (So if there's 10 questions and you're a fast programmer, it's 10 pages of code to do what you want.)

What you can do is build up a dictionary that stores information, such as input arrays, input questions, output questions, and the answers. When you see an input question, you can look into your dictionary and figure out the information you'll need to store your question variables. Then, you can do whatever problem it is using the information you've gotten. Afterwards, when you input the output questions, when there's an output question that matches one of the input questions you've stored, you can load whatever information you need into the question variables and solve it.
